<h2 id="what-is-klaviyo">📧 What Is Klaviyo?</h2>

Klaviyo is an email and SMS marketing platform built specifically for ecommerce. Founded in 2012, it has become the de facto standard for Shopify Plus merchants and serious DTC brands. The platform differentiates through deep data integration, predictive analytics, and granular segmentation capabilities that competitors struggle to match.

Unlike generic email platforms like Mailchimp or Constant Contact, Klaviyo ingests your entire customer data profile — purchase history, browsing behavior, predicted lifetime value, churn risk — and makes that data actionable in your campaigns. For operators managing [customer relationship tools](/reviews/customer-relationship-management-tools) across multiple channels, this depth matters.

The platform serves over 150,000 brands in 2026, with particular strength in fashion, beauty, food and beverage, and home goods ecommerce. Recent additions include enhanced AI content generation, expanded CDP (Customer Data Platform) functionality, and improved multi-storefront management.

<h2 id="what-is-postscript">💬 What Is Postscript?</h2>

Postscript started as an SMS-only platform and has evolved into a conversational commerce tool with email capabilities added in 2024. The platform excels at two-way messaging, subscriber acquisition through checkout opt-ins, and compliance management for SMS marketing.

Where Klaviyo treats SMS as an extension of email, Postscript treats text messaging as the primary channel. This philosophical difference shapes everything from their flow builders to their analytics dashboards. For operators whose customers prefer text communication — particularly in food service, local retail, and service businesses — Postscript's SMS-first approach produces higher engagement rates.

The platform integrates with major ecommerce platforms but lacks Klaviyo's depth of data ingestion. You're trading analytical sophistication for conversational capability.

<h2 id="what-is-omnisend">🔄 What Is Omnisend?</h2>

Omnisend positions itself as the all-in-one marketing automation platform for growing ecommerce brands. The platform combines email, SMS, push notifications, and basic pop-up tools in a single interface at a price point significantly below Klaviyo.

Founded in 2014, Omnisend has carved out a niche serving small to mid-sized ecommerce operations that need solid fundamentals without enterprise complexity. The platform offers pre-built automation workflows, decent segmentation, and integrated SMS — all in a package that costs 40-60% less than Klaviyo at comparable list sizes.

For operators who need guidance on [choosing the right marketing stack](/guides/building-your-marketing-technology-stack), Omnisend represents the pragmatic middle ground.

<h2 id="our-experience">🏢 Our Experience Managing Email at Scale</h2>

Our team has deployed these three platforms across 47 ecommerce operations over the past four years, ranging from single Shopify stores to multi-location retailers with 15+ storefronts and unified inventory systems. We've migrated between platforms, run A/B tests on identical customer segments, and tracked revenue attribution across 18-month periods.

The patterns that emerge from this experience differ significantly from what vendor case studies suggest.

Klaviyo's strength becomes undeniable once you're managing customer data across multiple touchpoints. We implemented Klaviyo for a 12-location sporting goods retailer and saw abandoned cart recovery rates increase 34% compared to their previous Mailchimp setup — primarily because Klaviyo's browse abandonment flows caught customers earlier in the purchase journey.

However, Klaviyo's pricing model punishes list growth aggressively. One client's monthly costs jumped from $700 to $2,100 when their list grew from 50K to 120K subscribers during a successful holiday season. The revenue justified it, but the sticker shock caught their finance team off guard.

Postscript delivered the highest engagement rates we've measured — 98% open rates and 36% click rates on SMS campaigns for a fast-casual restaurant chain. But their email tools feel bolted-on rather than native. When clients asked us to build sophisticated email flows, we found ourselves recommending they keep Klaviyo for email and use Postscript solely for SMS.

Omnisend surprised us with capability relative to price. For a boutique retailer doing $800K annually, Omnisend's $79/month plan delivered 90% of what they'd get from Klaviyo at $350/month. The segmentation isn't as granular, the predictive analytics don't exist, but the core workflows — welcome series, abandoned cart, post-purchase — performed within 15% of our Klaviyo benchmarks.

